---
title: Web & graphic design in the age of AI
excerpt: AI has collapsed the cost of producing design — logos in seconds, websites in an afternoon. After 25 years in this craft, here's what I think that actually changes, what it doesn't, and what you should be paying a designer for now.
date: '2026-07-09'
category: AI
draft: false
---

I've been a graphic designer for twenty-five years. Long enough to remember when "the tools changed everything" meant desktop publishing, then the web, then smartphones. Each time, part of the trade died, part of it got cheaper, and the part that mattered — knowing what's good — quietly became more valuable.

AI is the fourth wave I've worked through, and it's the biggest. But the pattern is the same. Let me tell you what I see from inside the studio, because most of what's written about AI and design is written by people selling one or panicking about the other.

## Production just became nearly free

Let's start with the honest part: a large share of what clients used to pay designers for is now cheap.

A serviceable logo in thirty seconds. A landing page from a one-line prompt. Product photos that were never photographed. Ten social variants of a campaign visual before your coffee is done. This is real, it works, and pretending otherwise is how a designer becomes a nostalgia act.

I know because I use these tools every day. This website — the one you're reading — was designed in my studio and then **written in code with Claude**. Not assembled in a page builder, not squeezed out of a template: designed like I've always designed, then built by describing intent to a machine that types faster than any developer I've ever hired. What used to take a team weeks took days.

So yes: if your mental model of a designer is "someone who operates the software," that job is evaporating. I operated the software for twenty-five years. The software now operates itself.

## What AI actually produces

Here's what those thirty-second logos have in common, though: they're all *plausible*. Plausible is what these systems are built to produce — the statistically likely answer, the average of everything they've seen. And the average of everything is, by definition, what everyone else already looks like.

Plausible is fine when nothing is at stake. But a brand is a bet that you are *not* interchangeable. The whole commercial point of design is differentiation — one clear idea, held with discipline, applied everywhere. That's not a production problem. It was never a production problem. Cheap production doesn't solve it; cheap production makes it *worse*, because now everyone's plausible-average output is flooding the same feeds, the same search results, the same streets.

When everyone can produce, sameness becomes the default. Distinctiveness becomes the scarce good.

## The judgment didn't get automated

What the last two years have taught me is that AI moved the bottleneck; it didn't remove it. The bottleneck used to be hands. Now it's judgment.

Somebody still has to decide what the brief actually is — clients almost never bring the real problem in the first sentence. Somebody has to look at forty plausible options and know why the thirty-ninth is the only one that will still work in five years, printed one-color on the side of a van. Somebody has to say *no* — to the trend, to the fourth typeface, to the clever idea that doesn't fit the strategy. Somebody has to hold the system together over years, so the brand doesn't dissolve into whatever each new tool suggests.

Twenty-five years of shipped work is not sentimental capital. It's a training set — mine — full of press checks that went wrong, logos that failed in favicon size, and identities that survived three redesign attempts because the original idea was strong. AI has read everything, but it hasn't *shipped* anything. It has never had a client, a budget, or a consequence.

## What this did to web design

The web is where the shift is most dramatic, and — oddly — where it's best news for clients.

For fifteen years, small-business websites meant a stack of compromises: a theme someone else designed, a page builder rendering bloated markup, a plugin pile that needs feeding, hosting that groans under all of it. Custom-coded sites were better in every measurable way, but the economics were absurd for a small company — designer plus developer plus project manager plus a five-figure invoice.

AI broke that equation. A designer who can direct a coding model can now deliver what only agencies could: a site designed for the brand and *written in code* — static, fast, semantically clean, with every meta tag and every line of structured data placed deliberately. No template tax. No plugin rot. And it costs what the template-shop work used to.

This matters more right now than it ever has, because how people find you is changing at the same time. Search is splitting into classic Google and AI assistants that read, summarize and quote the web. Both reward the same thing: clean, fast, legible HTML that says what it means. Page builders are bad at this. Hand-written code is perfect at it — and hand-written code is exactly what became affordable.

The irony is lovely: AI, which supposedly kills craft, just made the craftsman's way of building websites economically viable again.

## What to buy from a designer now

If you're hiring design in 2026, here's my honest advice — the same advice I give clients who ask why they shouldn't just prompt something themselves:

- **Don't pay for production.** Volume, variants, resizes, routine artwork — that's cheap now, and any designer still billing big hours for it is billing you for the past.
- **Pay for the decision.** The brief, the idea, the choice among the options, the discipline to keep it consistent. This is the part that compounds. It's also the part that was always underpriced.
- **Pay for the system, not the deliverable.** A logo is a file. An identity is a set of rules that makes the next hundred decisions automatic. Files are cheap; rules are valuable.
- **For websites, insist on code you can keep.** Whoever builds it, and with whatever tools — the result should be fast, readable HTML that belongs to you. If it only exists inside a builder's subscription, you're renting your own front door.
- **Expect your designer to use AI — openly.** A designer who refuses the tools is charging you for friction. A designer who *only* has the tools is charging you for the average. You want the one who uses the machine and keeps the taste.

## The craft is fine

Every wave I've worked through produced the same two panics: the old guard declaring the craft dead, and the tool-sellers declaring the craftsman obsolete. Both wrong, every time.

Design was never the software. Design is deciding what something should be, and having the taste and the spine to hold that decision under pressure. Machines now do the typing — in Illustrator and, remarkably, in code. Good. Typing was never the valuable part.

Twenty-five years in, I get to spend my hours almost entirely on the part I signed up for. The machines handle the plausible. Someone still has to be responsible for what's *good*.

